recordings.loc: Victoria, Capital, British Columbia
recordings.rmk:
This male Eurasian Wigeon is in a large group of several hundred American Wigeons and Mallards.  Although the Eurasian Wigeon is not banded, we have seen a male Eurasian Wigeon for the past three years on the same side of the same pond in the same park.  He remains in the park during the entire winter.   Although he is normally quiet during the winter and we have seldom heard him call before, on this day there was heavy snow and the entire flock was feeding on the grass.  The male Eurasian Wigeon calls at 3, 9, and 19 seconds into the recording, when mallards approached him while he is feeding.  The recording was made about 2 meters from the male Eurasian Wigeon.

I have a longer recording (more than 3 minutes) and 8 photos of the Eurasian Wigeon, if interested.

recordings.rmk:
This is a recording of group of about 120 American Wigeons that spend most nights in this area during winter.  The group is generally silent except for calls from 1 or 2 birds, except when small groups of other Wigeons arrive.  This recording includes calls during the separate arrivals of 4 groups of smaller numbers of Wigeons.  There are calls from some of the new arrivals, as they swim closer, and a chorus of calls from the established larger group. 

The recording is made at 9:30 p.m., more than 5 hours after 4:22 p.m. sunset.  The Wigeons are a resting in the ocean 1 to 5 meters from a sandy beach.  There are about a dozen Mallards resting on the beach.  There is a Great Blue Heron resting on a nearby rock but is not heard in this recording.

recordings.rmk:
Two individuals emerged from separate reedbeds in flooded grasslands and began shoving each other for about 10 seconds.  During 5 to 10 seconds after start of this recording, they jumped up and hit each other while both were calling.  They did not use their bills for attacking but limited their physical encounter to shoving and hitting their bodies.  It did not seem to be an encounter in which they were likely to injure each other. They then moved apart before each retreated into separate reedbeds.  During 22 to 28 seconds after the start of this recording, one individual called before both individuals remained silent.

This recording was made on the northern edge of Swan Lake, two days after heavy rains flooded the lake's surrounding grasslands.  Main trails were still flooded and many bird species moved out of lake areas into surrounding flooded grasslands and forests.  At least six Virginia Rails were observed in one hour in the flooded areas, which is a larger number that usually seen.

recordings.rmk: Calls from adult Chestnut-backed Chickadee (presumed female) given while following and foraging in close proximity with a second adult (presumably its mate).  These are typical calls given by adults (only females?) in the early part of the breeding season, at times accompanied by crouching and wing-fluttering by the vocalizing birds during submissive/begging behaviour. recordings.loc: Rainbow Park (near  Victoria), Capital, British Columbia
recordings.rmk: Begging calls from single juvenile.  I have been watching the nest: this juvenile left the nest about 8 days ago.  It lacks flight feathers and spends most of the time hiding under dense shrubs.  At the beginning of the recording, the juvenile calls occasionally while the adult feeds on the open grass 5 to 10 meters away.  Toward the last portion of the recording, the adult returns to the juvenile, at which point the juvenile calls continuously, the adult opens its mouth, and juvenile feeds.  Afterwards, the adult departs and the begging calls cease.  I used a moderate high pass filter at  4000 Hz to reduce noise from three floatplanes.

Calls and songs from several individuals feeding on ground and close to ground in bushes in flooded wetlands.

Main trails were still flooded and many bird species moved out of lake areas into surrounding flooded grasslands and forests.  At least six Virginia Rails were observed in one hour in the flooded areas, which is a larger number that usually seen.
